Inside This Section





        More About NADA
    



The NADA Story                                                                  
    

The NADA story began in 1917 when 30 auto dealers traveled to the nation’s capital to convince Congress not to impose a luxury tax on the automobile. They successfully argued that the automobile is a necessity of American life, not a luxury. From that experience, NADA was born. Today, NADA represents nearly 16,500 new-car and -truck dealers, with 32,500 franchises, both domestic and international.




Mission Statement                                                             
    

The purpose of the National Automobile Dealers Association is to serve and represent the franchised new-car and -truck dealers of America, their management and employees.                                                                           
    
NADA has two main goals:                                                                           
    
1. To promote and enhance the franchise system and effectively communicate dealer views and concerns to all branches of the federal government, to manufacturers, and the public; and                                                                      
        
    
2. To strengthen the financial position of members as retailers through professional programs and services that improve the business skills of management personnel and the technical capabilities of non-management employees.




































Deboer, Sidney B. - The Wall Street Transcript













































 





































Sidney B. Deboer
SIDNEY B. DEBOER is the Chairman and Chief Executive Officer of Lithia
Motors, Inc. His professional background began in 1964, working for his
father as an Office Manager in an automobile dealership. From 1966 to
1968 he sold cars. Afterwards he became a Dodge dealer in Ashland,
Oregon and has been managing dealerships ever since. Mr. DeBoer attended
the University of Oregon where he studied Business Education and the
University of Oregon where he majored in Accounting. From 1983 to 1997
he has received numerous awards, the latest being ‘Time Magazine Quality
Dealer Award’ in 1997. His professional memberships include: American
Import Automotive Dealers Association; Chrysler Dealer Council; Honda
Dealer Council; Medford New Car Dealers Association; National Auto
Dealers Association; Oregon Auto Dealers Association; and Toyota Dealers
Council.
