Footnotes / references
Financial data.[1]


Lithia Motors, Inc. is an American nationwide automotive dealership network headquartered in Medford, Oregon. It is the fourth largest automotive retailer[2] in the United States. Lithia Motors, Inc. ranked #602 on Fortune's top 1000 companies in 2014 list, up from a rank of #653 in 2013.[3] In 2015, Lithia Motors broke into the Fortune 500 list at #482,[4] making it one of only three Oregon-based companies in the Fortune 500.[5] This followed a year that saw the acquisition of the DCH Auto Group, one of the 10 largest dealer groups in the country with 27 dealerships, before being purchased by Lithia Motors.[6] In 2016, Lithia climbed to #346 and that same year, made the Fortune 500 List of Top Ten Companies with the biggest Jump in rank on the Fortune 500.[7] Today, Lithia employs more than 11,000 people in stores across the nation including Alaska and Hawaii.[8] Lithia operates 150 stores in 16 states.[9]




Contents


1 History
2 Product
3 Recent financials
4 Community programs
5 See also
6 References



History[edit]
Lithia Motors began in 1946 when Walt DeBoer opened a single car dealership in Ashland, Oregon. The first year the five person company sold 14 cars. In 1968, Walt's son, Sidney DeBoer, took over the business and incorporated Lithia Motors Inc. Sidney reorganized the business and in 1970 purchased a Dodge dealership in Medford. With this, Lithia’s base of operation moved to Medford and grew to a total of five stores with 19 franchises by 1990.[10]
In December 1996 the company went public, trading on the New York Stock Exchange with an IPO of $11 per share.[10] By 2003, Lithia had revenues of $2.5 billion from its 84 dealerships while employing just over 5,500 people.[11] The company had increased dealerships to 88 by 2005.[12] Lithia was fined $500,000 by the state of Alaska in 2006 for charging car buyers illegal document preparation fees at their Alaska dealerships.[13] That year they also settled with the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission for workplace discrimination.[14] In early 2007 began plans to build a 60-acre (240,000 m2) auto mall north of downtown Medford and to build a new corporate headquarters in downtown Medford. The Chrysler Jeep Dodge store moved to the auto mall in September 2007 but the project was put on hold for seven years because the recession hit shortly after. In late 2014, Lithia moved their Honda, Nissan, BMW, and Volkswagen stores to the auto mall. The group's Toyota store, which the group had planned to move to the auto mall, instead went through a $1.5 million renovation in 2013 and stayed on their 5-acre site in downtown Medford. [15] In 2010, it was reported that with the backing of two lenders, “the Commons”, a mixed-use building with Lithia Headquarters as the largest tenant, was a “go” and could proceed with construction. According to an article by The Mail Tribune, “Lithia partnered with the Medford Urban Renewal Agency to create The Commons, a revitalization project that includes the headquarters and another $14 million in infrastructure and three park blocks paid for with MURA dollars.[16] Lithia employees moved into their new headquarters in late 2012. In January, 2014 the Commons building was awarded Silver Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Certification by the U.S. Green Building Council.[17] Lithia has been the recipient of numerous awards, including Sports Illustrated's All-Star Dealer Award in 1990 and Time's Quality Dealer Award in 1997, 2016 Top Workplace-Oregon Award[18], 2016 Automotive News Best Dealerships to Work For[19] and 2016 Fortune 500-40th Fastest Growing Company.[20]




Headquarters in Medford, Oregon


As of January, 2014, Lithia operated 92 stores in 13 states.[21]
With the acquisition of the DCH auto group in late 2014, Lithia expanded to 139 stores in 14 states across the US, Hawaii, and Alaska.
In September 2016, Lithia Motors partnered with Carbone Auto Group bringing the Lithia Motors, Inc. store number to 150.[22]
Product[edit]
Lithia sells new cars from General Motors, Chrysler, Toyota, Honda, BMW, Volkswagen, Mazda, and Porsche among others.[23] New cars make up 58% of auto sales, with used cars making up the other 42%.[23] Additional revenues come from auto repair at the dealerships, financing, and insurance sales.[23]
In 2013 Lithia was named No. 9 on Automotive News' list of the 125 largest U.S. dealership groups, with retail new-vehicle sales of 56,960 units in 2012. In used-vehicle sales it also ranks No. 9, with retail used-vehicle sales of 49,067 in 2012.[24]
The company received a Global Automotive Shareholder Value Awards presented by PwC and Automotive News in 2015 the sixth consecutive year for Lithia, followed by a three-year award in 2016[25]. The awards are given to companies to recognize the highest shareholder returns within one-year and three-year periods among Global Vehicle Manufacturers, Global Automotive Suppliers and U.S. Automotive Retailers categories.[26]
2016 New Vehicle Revenue: $4,938,436, Used Vehicle Revenue: $2,226,951[27]
